id: automation/yawn.bot.ai-writing-scan
title: "yawn.bot AI-writing scan"
kind: automation-contract
status: active
updated: 2026-07-01

automation_id: yawn-bot-ai-writing-scan
schedule: "twice daily at 10:30 AM and 4:30 PM America/Denver"
runtime: "Codex app cron automation"
workspaces:
  - "C:/Users/dave/OneDrive/Documents/MASTER-CONTROL.YAWN"
  - "C:/Users/dave/OneDrive/Documents/yawn-ai-homepage"
policy: agents/yawn.bot.policy.yawn
ledger: records/yawn.bot-ai-writing-ledger.yawn
external_reference: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Signs_of_AI_writing"

purpose: >
  Scan public .yawn repository text and yawn.ai homepage text for language that
  sounds generically AI-generated, over-polished, canned, promotional, or
  mechanically patterned, then recommend bounded human-voice rewrites.

why_added: >
  The phrase "The app can come later. The graph can come later. The game world
  can come later. The agent cockpit can come later." reached readme.yawn because
  existing audits focused on comprehension, license risk, privacy, and source
  correctness, but did not explicitly check for canned parallel rhythm or
  AI-shaped prose.

scan_scope:
  source_repo:
    include:
      - "*.yawn"
      - "*.ion"
      - "*.md"
      - "*.html"
      - "*.yml"
    exclude:
      - ".git"
  homepage:
    include:
      - "README.md"
      - "AGENTS.md"
      - "CLAUDE.md"
      - ".yawn-source-bridge.json"
      - "src/**/*.ts"
      - "src/**/*.tsx"
    exclude:
      - ".git"
      - ".next"
      - "node_modules"
      - "package-lock.json"

signals_to_check:
  - repeated parallel ladders such as "X can come later" or "not only X, but also Y"
  - rule-of-three filler that sounds rhythmic but does not add meaning
  - vague significance, legacy, broader-trend, or "plays a key role" phrasing
  - promotional, advertisement-like, or high-gloss funnel language without proof
  - generic conclusions about challenges, future prospects, or unlocking potential
  - overuse of AI-vocabulary words such as leverage, robust, seamless, transformative, holistic, nuanced, crucial, pivotal, or underscores
  - collaborative assistant residue such as "of course", "certainly", "I hope this helps", "let me know", or "would you like"
  - markdown or citation artifacts from model output such as turn0search0, oaicite, contentReference, attributableIndex, or placeholder template text
  - abrupt style shifts between adjacent sections
  - sections that sound polished but remove concrete Yawn words, proof, body, file, or next-move specificity

review_rules:
  - Treat AI-writing signs as review signals, not proof of AI authorship.
  - Quote only the smallest needed excerpt.
  - Record file path, line, signal type, severity, false-positive possibility, and suggested rewrite.
  - Prefer plainer, more specific Yawn language over generic sophistication.
  - Preserve intentional repetition when it carries meaning, ritual, or memorable interface structure.
  - Do not use AI-detection scores as authority.
  - Do not shame authors or accuse a human of using AI.

severity:
  low: "minor polish smell; leave unless nearby work touches it"
  medium: "noticeable canned rhythm or generic phrasing; suggest rewrite"
  high: "public-facing text sounds model-generated, promotional, or misleading; recommend immediate rewrite"

output:
  - files scanned
  - suspicious excerpts with line references
  - signal category
  - severity
  - why this may be a false positive
  - smallest rewrite suggestion
  - whether the issue should update README, homepage, or automation rules
  - commit-readiness state

blocked:
  - declare text AI-generated as fact
  - rely on external AI detectors as proof
  - rewrite private or generated dependency files
  - scan node_modules or build output
  - make commits, pushes, comments, PRs, or deployments without explicit current human authorization

proof:
  source:
    - 08-research/july-01-2026-ai-writing-scan-lock.ion
    - records/yawn.bot-ai-writing-ledger.yawn
    - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Signs_of_AI_writing
  status: seed-backed
